tissue volume?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Communicating hydrocephalus","Sagittal sinus thrombosis","Subarachnoid haemorrhage","Traumatic brain injury","Venous sinus thrombosis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETraumatic brain injury\u003C/strong\u003E causes cytotoxic and vasogenic oedema, directly increasing brain tissue volume. This leads to raised intracranial pressure through expansion of the brain parenchyma itself.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options primarily raise intracranial pressure through other mechanisms:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVenous sinus thrombosis\u003C/strong\u003E causes increased blood volume due to impaired venous drainage\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommunicating hydrocephalus\u003C/strong\u003E increases cerebrospinal fluid volume due to impaired absorption\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubarachnoid haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E increases blood volume in the subarachnoid space\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESagittal sinus thrombosis\u003C/strong\u003E causes increased blood volume through venous congestion\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAccording to the Monro-Kellie doctrine, the skull contains brain tissue, blood, and cerebrospinal fluid in a state of volume equilibrium. An increase in any component can raise intracranial pressure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intracranial pressure can rise due to increases in any of the three intracranial components: brain tissue, blood volume, or cerebrospinal fluid volume.","Brain oedema in traumatic brain injury directly increases brain tissue volume leading to raised intracranial pressure.","Venous sinus thrombosis causes raised intracranial pressure primarily through increased blood volume, not tissue volume."],"references":["Galgano M, Toshkezi G, Qiu X, Russell T, Chin L, Zhao LR. Traumatic Brain Injury: Current Treatment Strategies and Future Endeavors. Cell Transplant. 2017 Jul;26(7):1118-1130. doi: 10.1177/0963689717714102. PMID: 28933211; PMCID: PMC5657730.","Mckee AC, Daneshvar DH. The neuropathology of traumatic brain injury. Handb Clin Neurol. 2015;127:45-66. doi: 10.1016/B978-0-444-52892-6.00004-0. PMID: 25702209; PMCID: PMC4694720.","Bourke NJ, Demarchi C, De Simoni S, Samra R, Patel MC, Kuczynski A, Mok Q, Wimalasundera N, Vargha-Khadem F, Sharp DJ. Brain volume abnormalities and clinical outcomes following paediatric traumatic brain injury. Brain. 2022 Aug 27;145(8):2920-2934. doi: 10.1093/brain/awac130. PMID: 35798350; PMCID: PMC9420021.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51502"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16575"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51502","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51502"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-29T09:17:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-29T09:18:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9266"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66045"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups